data.text: TanStack Query v5: A Guide to Installation and Basic Fetch Example

When building modern web applications, managing server state efficiently is crucial. TanStack Query (formerly React Query) has become the go-to library for handling server state in React applications, thanks to its powerful caching, automatic refetching, and effortless integration. With the release of TanStack Query v5, things get even better. This blog walks you through installing the library and implementing a basic fetch example.
TanStack Query v5 introduces enhanced features and better developer experience, including:

items.content: Increased modularity to work seamlessly across frameworks.

data.text: To get started with TanStack Query, first, you need to install the core library and React adapter. Use your favorite package manager (npm, yarn, or pnpm).

data.code:
# Using npm
npm install @tanstack/react-query

# Using yarn
yarn add @tanstack/react-query

# Using pnpm
pnpm add @tanstack/react-query

data.text: If you want to use Devtools (highly recommended during development), install them as well:

data.code:
# Using npm
npm install @tanstack/react-query-devtools

# Using yarn
yarn add @tanstack/react-query-devtools

# Using pnpm
pnpm add @tanstack/react-query-devtools

items.content: Create a Query Client: TanStack Query requires a QueryClient instance to manage your queries.
Wrap Your Application: Use the QueryClientProvider to wrap your React application.

TanStack Query v5 continues to simplify data fetching and state management for modern web applications. Its intuitive API and robust features make it an invaluable tool for developers. By following the steps above, you can quickly integrate TanStack Query into your project and enjoy its benefits.
Stay tuned for more advanced use cases, like mutations, query invalidation, and leveraging its caching capabilities to boost performance. Happy coding! 🚀
